c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Meta drops end-to-end encryption on Instagram"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"VPNs become a Band-Aid, not a solution"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Privacy trade-offs now baked into the platform"}]]}]]}]}]
d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["Meta’s quiet announcement that ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.pcgamesn.com/instagram/end-to-end-encryption-vpn-privacy","children":"Instagram will discontinue end-to-end encryption"}]," isn’t just another settings tweak. It’s a fundamental shift in how the platform treats your data—one that moves privacy from a default to a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"luxury"}],". For users who relied on Instagram’s encrypted DMs to share sensitive info (think activists, journalists, or even just folks swapping unfiltered opinions), this isn’t theoretical. It’s a workflow disruption with immediate costs: either accept surveillance-level exposure or scramble for workarounds like VPNs, which, let’s be clear, ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://restoreprivacy.com/vpn-misconceptions/","children":"don’t encrypt your messages"}],"—they just obscure your IP address.\nThe timing isn’t accidental. Meta’s ad business thrives on granular user data, and encrypted DMs were a rare blind spot. Removing that friction aligns with the company’s ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.theverge.com/2023/5/10/23717922/meta-messenger-ads-dms-instagram-whatsapp","children":"long-term push to monetize private interactions"}],", from ads in Messenger to AI-powered ‘helpful’ suggestions in chats. The message to users? Privacy is negotiable—unless you’re willing to jump through hoops.\nEarly signals suggest the change will roll out universally, but the ",["$","em",null,{"children":"real"}]," impact won’t be evenly distributed. High-profile accounts and businesses may shrug (they’re already public-facing), while marginalized groups or users in repressive regimes—who ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.wired.com/story/instagram-encryption-activists/","children":"rely on encrypted DMs to organize"}],"—face abrupt vulnerability. Meta’s framing this as a ‘trade-off for better features,’ but the math is clear: ",["$","em",null,{"children":"their"}]," features improve; ",["$","em",null,{"children":"your"}]," risks multiply."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/instagrams-encryption-retreat-why-vpns-wont-fix-th/subtitle.jpg","alt":"Kada zaštita podataka postane opcionalna — tko zapravo plaća cijenu?","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"Kada zaštita podataka postane *opcionalna* — tko zapravo plaća cijenu?"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["Here’s where the VPN sales pitches get loud—and misleading. Yes, a VPN can hide your location from Instagram’s servers, but it won’t stop Meta from scanning your DMs for ad targeting or ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2023/06/meta-expands-data-sharing-government-agencies","children":"complying with government data requests"}],". The practical gap is stark: VPNs protect ",["$","em",null,{"children":"transit"}]," (your connection), not ",["$","em",null,{"children":"content"}]," (your messages). For most users, that’s like locking the front door while leaving the windows wide open.\nThe broader ecosystem effect is already rippling. Competitors like Signal and Telegram are ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://techcrunch.com/2024/02/15/signal-telegram-growth-after-instagram-encryption-news/","children":"seeing upticks in downloads"}],", but switching platforms isn’t seamless. Instagram’s network effects—its 1.4 billion users, its cultural dominance—make exodus costly. Developers building privacy tools now face a dilemma: do they integrate with a platform that’s actively degrading security, or cede ground to Meta’s walled garden?\nRegulators, meanwhile, are watching—but not acting. The EU’s Digital Services Act ","$L15"," around data use, but enforcement lags. In the U.S., where privacy laws are patchwork at best, Meta’s move sets a precedent: if Instagram can backtrack on encryption, what’s next? Passwordless logins? AI-trained on your DMs? The slippery slope isn’t theoretical; it’s the ","$L16",".\nFor now, users are left with a binary choice: adapt or opt out. But the real question isn’t about VPNs or alternatives—it’s whether we’ve normalized platforms treating privacy as a ","$L17"," rather than a right."]}]]}]
